Interface LinkedListInterface<T>

  • All Known Implementing Classes:
    CircularDoublyLinkedList

    public interface LinkedListInterface<T>
    This interface describes the public methods needed for CircularDoublyLinkedList, which should be circular, doubly linked, and have a head pointer. We've given you the expected Big-O for each method this time around. DO NOT ALTER THIS FILE!!

    • Method Detail

      • addAtIndex

        void addAtIndex(int index,
                T data)
        Adds the element to the index specified. Adding to index 0 and (size) should be O(1), all other adds are O(n). Throw java.lang.IndexOutOfBoundsException if index is negative or index > size. Throw java.lang.IllegalArgumentException if data is null.
        Parameters:
        index - The index where you want the new element.
        data - Any object of type T.
        Throws:
        java.lang.IndexOutOfBoundsException - if index is negative or index > size
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if data is null.

      • addToFront

        void addToFront(T data)
        Add a new node to the front of your linked list that holds the given data. Make sure to update head. Must be O(1). Throw java.lang.IllegalArgumentException if data is null.
        Parameters:
        data - The data that the new node should hold.
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if data is null.

      • addToBack

        void addToBack(T data)
        Add a new node to the back of your linked list that holds the given data. Must be O(1). Throw java.lang.IllegalArgumentException if data is null.
        Parameters:
        data - The data that the new node should hold.
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if data is null.

      • get

        T get(int index)
        Returns the element at the given index. This method must be O(1) for index 0 and (size - 1). O(n) is expected for all other indices. Throw java.lang.IndexOutOfBoundsException if index < 0 or index >= size.
        Parameters:
        index - The index of the element
        Returns:
        The object stored at that index.
        Throws:
        java.lang.IndexOutOfBoundsException - if index < 0 or index >= size.

      • removeAtIndex

        T removeAtIndex(int index)
        Removes and returns the element at index. This method should be O(1) for index 0 and (size - 1), and O(n) in all other cases. Throw java.lang.IndexOutOfBoundsException if index < 0 or index >= size.
        Parameters:
        index - The index of the element
        Returns:
        The object that was formerly at that index.
        Throws:
        java.lang.IndexOutOfBoundsException - if index < 0 or index >= size.

      • removeFromFront

        T removeFromFront()
        Remove the front node from the list and return the data from it. If the list is empty, return null. Must be O(1).
        Returns:
        The data from the front node or null.

      • removeFromBack

        T removeFromBack()
        Remove the back node from the list and return the data from it. If the list is empty, return null. Must be O(1).
        Returns:
        The data from the last node or null.

      • removeFirstOccurrence

        int removeFirstOccurrence(T data)
        Remove the first occurrence of data in the linked list. Must be O(n). Throw java.util.NoSuchElementException if data is not in the list. Throw java.lang.IllegalArgumentException if data is null.
        Parameters:
        data - The data to be removed from the list.
        Returns:
        the index of the occurrence that was removed from the list.
        Throws:
        java.util.NoSuchElementException - if data is not in the list.
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if data is null.

      • removeAllOccurrences

        boolean removeAllOccurrences(T data)
        Remove all occurrences of data in the linked list. Must be O(n). Throw java.lang.IllegalArgumentException if data is null.
        Parameters:
        data - The data to be removed from the list.
        Returns:
        true if anything was removed from the list; otherwise, false.
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if data is null.

      • toArray

        java.lang.Object[] toArray()
        Return the linked list represented as an array of objects. If the list is empty, return an empty array. Must be O(n).
        Returns:
        A copy of the linked list data as an array.

      • isEmpty

        boolean isEmpty()
        Return a boolean value representing whether or not the list is empty. Must be O(1).
        Returns:
        True if empty. False otherwise.

      • size

        int size()
        Return the size of the list as an integer. Must be O(1).
        Returns:
        The size of the list.

      • clear

        void clear()
        Clear the list. Must be O(1).

      • getHead

        LinkedListNode<T> getHead()
        Reference to the head node of the linked list. Normally, you would not do this, but we need it for grading your work.
        Returns:
        Node representing the head of the linked list.
